media.altText:
Kolakowsky-Hayner et al (2021). The COVID-19 pandemic: Age differences in sleep quality and mental health across 59 Countries. Epidemiology and Public Health Research, 1(1), 1-10. DOI: 10.5281/zenodo.7686574

Study results indicated significant age differences, with younger participants reporting more sleep problems than older group. Results may reflect additional vulnerability of younger populations to social isolation and other factors such as employment and economic insecurity during pandemic. Mental health symptoms & sleep disturbance may have a bidirectional association and have important implications treatment planning and symptom management. 
The results of this study underscore the importance and necessity to both evaluate and treat/improve sleep quality, especially in younger age group, in the general population not only during pandemic but also during post-pandemic recovery and during and post- long-COVID.

I really feel tremendous grief for friendships that kind of petered away in the face of life's currents. There are people with whom I formed deep, unique, vibrant, life-changing connections, and then we had to go our separate ways and it was too hard to maintain long-distance. There wasn't a fight, it just sort of faded. And I feel like I have more friendships like this than friendships that have endured, so maybe I just have to get used to it. But if grief is all the love we have left over - well, I never did get to finish loving them. I love them, and I miss them, and I probably always will.

content:
And the worst is when your paths have diverged so much that reaching out would just change that version you love, so you just keep on drifting further apart.

#introspection #depression #disabled https://t.co/OosGozGYIL
